field_edited_text.value:
SUMMARY 169

It would appear from the foregoing report that the four crossings included
in Maryland’s Primary Bridge Program would materially affect the traffic
situation in Baltimore, in Washington and in the sections of Maryland
through which these principal routes pass, by relieving the traffic congestion
and delay in passing through Baltimore; by creating an alternate route
south, and at the same time opening up Southern Maryland and the north-
ern neck of Virginia; by substituting an adequate four lane bridge for an
inadequate two lane bridge at Havre de Grace; and by providing an all
weather twenty-four hour highway connection directly between the eastern
and western shores of the state.
